{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\ulth\ulc0 \par \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0\ulc0 The People\rquote s Guide }{\fs20\ulc0 is a practical self-advocacy information guide and directory on how to get food, income, jobs and training, housing, health and dental care, legal advice, and other important help from local, state and federal programs and community services in Sacramento County.\par We don\rquote t need to tell you these are hard times!  Foreclosures, high unemployment, homelessness on the rise and the city, county, state and federal budgets either eliminating or making deep cuts to most of the programs talked about in this guide. \par These cuts mean less help for low-income individuals, families, seniors and homeless people to access the these life-saving programs.  It means reduced benefits, fewer workers, tighter eligibility rules, long lines and longer waits.  \par It also means rumors and false information that discourage eligible people from applying for a desperately needed program and people not knowing where or how to apply.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0\ulc0 The Sacramento Housing Alliance [SHA}{\fs20\ulc0 ] and the }{\f8\fs20\b\i0\ulc0 Sacramento Hunger Coalition [SHC] }
{\fs20\ulc0  believes that every person has the right to healthy food, safe, decent and affordable housing and healthcare.  Help in Hard Times not only is a self-advocacy guide to these programs, but also gives you advice on what you can do if your are treated unfairly or do not receive what you are entitled to by law.  The guide is dedicated to helping all people overcome barriers when they are trying to get help.\par You do not need to read the entire book; just find the topic in the table of contents.  But, remember, that if you are eligible for one kind of help, you often qualify for other programs.\par You can also help!\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0\ulc0 1. Share this information with other people who need help;}{\fs20\ulc0 \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0\ulc0 2. Share your voice:}
{\fs20\ulc0   Elected officials in Sacramento City, County, State Capitol and Washington, DC are always debating the programs and services described in this guide.  Especially during hard times, there is conflict about the money for these services.  Too often the programs described in this guide are eliminated or cut severely.\par Your voice is needed in these debates!  You are an expert on what happens to people\rquote s lives when they can\rquote t get food, money, housing or health care.  Government officials need to hear your authentic voice and remind them of how these programs help or don\rquote t help what your problems or solutions are.\par Politicians often use the money for other things than education, health, welfare and social services.  But, when the rich get richer and the poor get poorer, the gap has very bad effects on our entire society.   You can help close that gap.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0\ulc0 3. To get names and address of your local, state and federal elected officials}{\fs20\ulc0  call                                 \tab  (916) 875-6451 \par  (California Relay Service English 1-888-877-5379) \par or go to \par http://www.sacwiki.org/Local_Representatives\par }
