{\f8\fs28\b\i0\outl What Are My Child\rquote s Rights?     \par Summer Meals    \par }{\f8\fs56\b\i0 Healthcare\par }\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In March 2010, the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act (ACA) was signed into law. The goal of health reform is make sure that more Americans have insurance, either public or private. Medi-Cal, a state-subsidized healthcare, will expand to cover higher incomes.  More information about Medi-Cal, eligibility and the application process is below. \par Starting in January 2014, if you do not qualify for Medi-Cal or another public health care program, you will be required to have another means of health insurance. Even if you do not qualify for Medi-Cal, you may be eligible for the Premium Assistance Program. This can help to reduce the cost of your health insurance premium, which is the amount of money you pay to buy health insurance coverage each month. Depending on your income, Cost Sharing Assistance can reduce the amount of health care expenses an individual has to pay when getting care. These expenses include copayments and other health care bills. \par Covered California\rquote s Health Benefit Exchange marketplace can help you find affordable health plans and answer any questions you may have. Visit www.coveredca.com or call 888-975-1142. To calculate an estimatead cost of healthcare, visit www.coveredca.com/calculating_the_cost.html. You may also contact Sacramento Covered at 1-866-850-4321 for assistance in finding a health plan. \par Starting January 1, 2014, you cannot be denied coverage because of a pre-existing condition (this has already begun for children under age 19). If you are a young adult under age 26, you can remain on your parents\rquote  private health coverage. (See www.health.lsnc.net/healthreform.) For more information on changes to private health insurance, visit www.coveredca.com.\line \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 \par \par \par Medi-Cal is a health insurance program to help pay the medical expenses of low income families, seniors, and people with disabilities.\par The state and federal government fund Medi-Cal. There are many Medi-Cal programs with different rules. Depending on which program you qualify for and how much money you make, Medi-Cal may pay for all your medical expenses or you might have to pay a share of the cost when you access health care services in a particular month. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Groups of Eligibility}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 You can get Medi-Cal if you:\par \'95 Meet  income and resource tests and\line \'95 Are a California resident and intend to stay in California   \tab   and\line \'95Fit within one of the eligible groups.\par The major groups who can get Medi-Cal are: \par \'95 People getting SSI, CalWORKs, foster care, adoption assistance, or certain immigrants receiving Entrant or Refugee Cash Assistance benefits. These groups get free Medi-Cal with no \ldblquote Share of Cost.\rdblquote \line \'95 Pregnant women\line \'95 Children under age 21\line \'95 Adults 65 or over\line \'95 People of any age who are disabled or blind by SSI guidelines (whether or not you are getting SSI) \line \'95 Families in which at least one parent is absent, deceased, disabled or unable to work, unemployed, or under-employed. \ldblquote Unemployed\rdblquote  means that the parent who has earned the most in the past two years is working less than 100 hours a month. \ldblquote Underemployed\rdblquote  means that the family\rquote s earned income is below the federal poverty level.\line \line \'95 Taking care of a related child under 21\line \'95 Refugees\line \'95 People living in a long term care facility\line \'95 People recieving dialysis for kidney failure\line \'95 People infected with tuberculosis (unless undocumented)\line \'95 Women (and some men) diagnosed with breast or cervical cancer. \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Besides fitting into one of the above categories, you must also meet certain income and resource limits. If your children are low income but get too much income to qualify for Medi-Cal, en\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Immigration Status }{\fs20 \par If you are a California resident and meet other Medi-Cal requirements, you can apply for a restricted Medi-Cal card, even if you\rquote re undocumented. This will pay for emergency services, pregnancy-related care and long term care services. \par Most low income legal immigrants can get regular (also called full-scope) Medi-Cal to cover most of their medically necessary health needs. \par Many immigrants can get full health coverage, even if they do not have a green card, for example those who are victims of domestic violence, or those in the process of adjusting their legal status (i.e., they are applying for Legal Permanent Residency).\par If you are receiving CalWORKs, SSI, foster care, or certain refugee benefits, you get Medi-Cal automatically and do not need to apply separately. \par \par \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \par }\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1.\u8239 ?Get an Application Form }{\fs20 \par You can get one mailed to you by calling the DHA toll-free number at 1 (888) 747-1222; or you can get one at a DHA Office. (See page 69); or you can get one at many hospitals and clinics, whether they are private or county-run. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Children Under Age 19}{\fs20  \par  You may apply for Medi-Cal for your children. Children who receive a CHDP visit are screened for temporary eligibility for Medi-Cal. If a child is eligible, he/she is pre-enrolled in temporary, full-scope  Medi-Cal at no cost for up to 60 days (for the month of the visit and the month after). \par Infants who were born to a woman recieving Medi-Cal at the time of birth should receive Medi-Cal ongoing until the age of one. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Filling Out the Application}{\fs20 \par You can get help filling out the application by calling (916) 874-3100.  A Medi-Cal worker will go over the application you filled out. If you are asked for more information, you will be given a list of what is needed and a specific date by which the information must be mailed to the Medi-Cal office. A "return appointment" is not necessary. \par  }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. Provide Needed Papers}{\fs20 \par \'95\u8239 ?Identification with your name and current address on it. For example, a birth certificate, driver\rquote s license, or California ID card.  If you lack ID, you can fill out a form called \ldblquote PA 853\rdblquote  and swear that you are who you say you are , or documents to verify income or disability status may also serve as proof of identity. \par \'95 Social Security Number or Card (or proof of application for the card) only for those requesting "full-scope" benefits. \par \'95 Proof of income (like check stubs,a copy of your tax return, a self-affidavit or statement of income if you are paid in cash or do not have any other way to prove income)\par \'95 Proof that you live in Sacramento County (a document that has your name and an address on it, such as an ID, a bill mailed to your house, school attendance records, pay stubs, etc.) for each adult on the application. \par \'95 Proof of U.S. citizenship and identity or acceptable immigration status for each person on the application who has declared acceptable immigration status.   If you are a parent applying for children only, you do not need to submit proof of your immigration status.\par \'95 Vehicle registration if ownership of more than one vehicle is declared. \par \'95 Verification of child or dependent care, educational expenses and/or health insurance premiums or court ordered child support payments can be used as deductions, but are not needed to determine eligibility.  \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 5. Cooperate With Child Support Services }{\fs20 \par If one parent is absent, most people will have to cooperate with DHA and a county agency called the Department of Child Support Services (DCSS.) You must provide information you have about the other parent such as an address or social security number, to establish who your child\rquote s absent father or mother is and whether that parent can provide the child with medical insurance. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 6. Wait for Approval}{\fs20 \par Normally, the Medi-Cal office will approve or deny your application within 45 days of receiving it, except for the faster ways for children, described above. If the state must evaluate a disability, the approval or denial can be delayed up to 90 days. If Medi-Cal denies your benefits, you can appeal. See pg. 67 for the \ldblquote Hearings and Complaints\rdblquote  section.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 7. The Medi-Cal Card}{\fs20 \par Once you have been \ldblquote approved,\rdblquote  you may ask your worker for a written verification of your eligibility status from the Medi-Cal Eligibility Data Systems (MEDS) or your medical provider may be able to use your Social Security Number to verify your eligibility status through their Point of Service system.\par Your permanent white plastic Medi-Cal card, called a \ldblquote Benefit Identification Card\rdblquote  or BIC, is mailed to your address. Each person listed on your application will get one, even if they aren\rquote t eligible for Medi-Cal, because if the family must pay a monthly Share of Cost, the medical expenses of every person listed on the application can be used to meet the Share of Cost. If you don\rquote t get your plastic card by the end of the month, or lose it, contact your worker. Keep the BIC even if your Medi-Cal stops. If you need Medi-Cal again, you can use the same BIC.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 8. Authorization For Service Under Fee-for-Service}{\fs20 \par Before certain medical services can be performed for you the state or your health plan has to give an authorization for the service. This is called a Treatment Authorization Request (TAR). \par This does NOT apply to emergency care, office visits, and most drugs. It is the job of the doctor, pharmacist, or other service provider, not the patient, to get this authorization from the state. \par However, if the state or health plan denies or changes the authorization, the state will notify you and your doctor. You can appeal any unreasonable delay, denial, reduction, or termination of care. (See pg. 67\rdblquote  "Hearings and Complaints") \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 9. If You Are Pregnant }{\fs20 \par If you are not more than 30 weeks pregnant and have too much income to be eligible for free Medi-Cal, you may be eligible for a program called AIM (Access for Infants and Mothers). Call AIM at (800) 433-2611. You can also get AIM even if you have medical insurance, if your insurance does not cover pregnancy or if you have a $500 "deductible".\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Many pregnant woman can get a temporary Medi-Cal card called "Presumptive Eligibility" immediately, without showing proof of pregnancy or providing information on property, car, or resources.  This will help you get early prenatal care, lab tests and medication. You still have to turn in a regular Medi-Cal application and provide proof of income by the end of the next month if you still need Medi-Cal.\par As soon as the baby is born call your worker to report the name and date to add the new baby to your family case record. The baby needs his or her own card by the end of the month after birth. However, you should not have to fill out a new Medi-Cal application for your baby.  If you have trouble reaching your worker to tell the worker about the birth of your baby, some WIC offices and clinics have \ldblquote Newborn Referral Forms\rdblquote  you can mail to DHA.  Or you can get one yourself on the internet at \par http://www.dhcs.ca.gov/formsandpubs/forms/Forms/mc330.pdf.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 10. If You Are Disabled }{\fs20 \par If you have certain severe physical or mental problems, (such as mental retardation or inability to walk) or if you have AIDS, you may also be able to get Medi-Cal based on disability even before the state determines you are disabled. This is called "Presumptive Disability". Bring medical reports that show you are disabled when you apply. Both children and adults can get disability Medi-Cal. \line \line The Medi-Cal Program for Aged and Disabled Persons provides  Medi-Cal services at no Share of Cost if you are not able to work and are 65 years of age or older or disabled. Information about the Working Disabled program is on page 25.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 11. Women (and Men) with Breast or Cervical Cancer}{\fs20 \par If you are under 65 without health insurance, or underinsured (you have high premiums, deductibles, co-payments or Share of Cost) and you have been both screened and diagnosed with breast or cervical cancer, you may get free Medi-Cal immediately and during the entire time you are receiving cancer  treatment, depending on your income.  There are no resource limits for this program.\par If you do not qualify for the above program because of age or immigration status, you may still get time limited Medi-Cal for cancer-related services only under a more limited \ldblquote state only\rdblquote  program.  Under that program, breast cancer treatment for men or women is limited to 18 months (which includes males who have been screened and diagnosed with breast cancer),  and cervical cancer treatment is limited to 24 months.  \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 12. Retroactive Benefits}{\fs20 \par If you had medical or pharmacy services from a Medi-Cal provider in the 3 months before you applied for Medi-Cal, ask your worker for a form to apply for \ldblquote retroactive benefits.\rdblquote  The mail-in application also asks if you want this. If you were eligible for Medi-Cal during those 3 months, Medi-Cal may pay those bills. If you\rquote ve already paid the bills and Medi-Cal covers the services, your clinic, doctor, dentist, or pharmacist should provide the refund to you.  If you have trouble getting a refund, call Legal Services at (916) 551-2150.\par \par \par \line Your countable income determines whether or not you can get Medi-Cal for free or whether you have to pay a \ldblquote Share of Cost.\rdblquote  (You only pay a "share of cost" in months when you actually use services.)  Certain types of income don\rquote t count or can be subtracted. The different Medi-Cal programs count the income limits differently. It\rquote s important when applying for Medi-Cal to report income and expenses including:\par \'95 Up to $175 (this may be subject to change) for child care for each child age 2 and over \par \'95 $200 (this may be subject to change) for childcare for each child under age two \par \'95 Court-ordered child and spousal support paid \par \'95 Child support received\par \'95 Educational expenses \par \'95 Business expenses of self-employed parents. \par Once a family qualifies for Medi-Cal, hundreds of dollars of their earnings might not count against their eligibility.\par Elderly (65 and older), blind or disabled persons can\tab  deduct (these amounts may be subject to change):\par \'95 $20 \par \'95 $65 from earned income \par \'95 Half of any remaining earned income \par \'95 Any health insurance premiums paid by you. \par Some elderly or disabled people, even though not receiving SSI, may get free Medi-Cal if the countable monthly income is less than a certain amount. This is called the \ldblquote Aged and Disabled Federal Poverty Level\rdblquote   Medi-Cal program. If you are over these limits you can still get Medi-Cal, but there will be a share of cost.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Special Low-Cost Medi-Cal for Working Disabled \tab Persons: }{\fs20 \par If you are a disabled working person or are married and both of you are working and disabled, you can get lower cost Medi-Cal if your income if you meet the income requirements. If you qualify, you will have to pay a monthly premium that goes up the more income that you have. Income deductions and exemptions apply, so apply even if you think your income may be too high; you can contact Legal Services of Northern California at (916) 551-2150 if you are denied. \par \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 \par \par The resource limit does not apply to pregnant women for care related to their pregnancy, or to children under 19 in certain Medi-Cal programs. For anyone else, your family\rquote s resources must be below certain limits to get Medi-Cal: \tab \par Some assets do not count. The home you live in, furnishings, personal items, and some non-term life insurance policies don\rquote t count. Other real estate may not count if you are not the only owner or are not able to sell it.  For some Medi-Cal programs one car does not count, and for some programs a car is not counted if its value is under a specific amount.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \par \par \par 1. Who Pays Share of Cost}{\fs20 \par Some people must pay, or agree to pay, a \ldblquote Share of Cost\rdblquote  for each month that they have a medical expense. Medi-Cal will then pay the rest of the bill for covered services that month. You do NOT have to pay a Share of Cost if: \par \'95 You are in one of the groups that receive free Medi-Cal (such as those getting CalWORKs, SSI, foster care, adoption assistance, 1931(b) Medi-Cal, or the aged and disabled programs).\par \'95 Your countable income is below certain income limits.\par If you have Medi-Cal with a Share of Cost, you begin each month with your Share of Cost limit. You don\rquote t have to pay anything in months that you have no medical expense. You can use past medical bills and the medical bills of family members listed on your application to meet your Share of Cost, including unpaid bills that they are trying to collect from you. You cannot count the same billed item or service twice, but you can carry the balance of an unpaid bill over to later months if a bill is for more than your Share of Cost. If your income goes down, notify your worker so your \ldblquote Share of Cost\rdblquote  will go down.}
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \par 2. Share of Cost: Children }{\fs20 \par Children whose income is too high for free Medi-Cal can get Medi-Cal with a Share of Cost (see the Childrens\rquote  Health Care section on page 28). You can find the premiums at 1-800 880-5305. Even if a child\rquote s parents start making more money and the parents have to start immediately paying a Share of Cost as a result, the child still receives Medi-Cal for free until their "Annual Redetermination." \par \par }
{\fs20 \par \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1.\u8239 ?Once a Year Eligibility Form}{\fs20 \par Individuals receiving Medi-Cal must have their eligibility rechecked (or \ldblquote redetermined\rdblquote ) every 12 months. You get a "redetermination packet" in the mail which you must fill out and send back.  You do not have to send in copies of documents with your redetermination form. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Mid-Year Status Report For Adults}{\fs20 \par Some adults recieving Medi-Cal must fill out the Mid-Year Status Report (MSR) in order to keep Medi-Cal.  Some groups of people do not have to fill our the MSR:  a child under 21; the parent or guardian of a CalWORKS child; pregnant women who have reported their pregnancy to the county, people who are disabled or over 65, or someone in the  Breast or Cervical Cancer Program. The report should come about 5 months after you start getting Medi-Cal and must be returned to the Medi-Cal office by the date on the form.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Reporting Changes for Adults }{\fs20 \par Adults must report to DHA any significant changes that may affect your eligibility within 10 days after the change. You must quickly report to your worker if you move, begin making more money (or less money), someone moves in or out of your house or you are pregnant. Even if you report a change that hurts your eligibility, you have important rights before the DHA cuts your Medi-Cal.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. Losing Welfare Does Not Mean That You Lose Medi-Cal }{\fs20 \par Leaving the CalWORKs program (for example because of a sanction, time-limit, or failure to comply with WTW rules) does not mean that you lose free Medi-Cal. If you lose your Medi-Cal after you leave welfare, contact Legal Services at (916) 551-2150 for help and advice. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 5. Transitional Medi-Cal }{\fs20 \par You might be eligible for up to 1 year of free (no Share of Cost) Medi-Cal (called transitional Medi-Cal or TMC) if you received CalWORKs or what is called "Section 1931(b) Medi-Cal" during at least 3 of the last 6 months, and you lost CalWORKs or Section 1931(b) Medi-Cal because you started making too much money. \par During the first six months of TMC, you and your family qualify for free Medi-Cal no matter how much income you have. \par After that, you remain eligible for TMC if you received TMC for the entire six months; you are still living in California;you remain employed; you have a child under 18 in the home; and you meet the income qualifications. \par Eligible families can receive TMC for up to one year. There is no lifetime limit on TMC. If your income goes down you can qualify again for regular Medi-Cal.   If it then goes up again you can return to TMC with new time limits. \par There are no \ldblquote resource\rdblquote  or property limits for TMC. TMC requires quarterly reports like a QR-7 for cash aid, but on a different form.\tab \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 6. Four Month Continuing  Medi-Cal }{\fs20 \par If you lose CalWORKs or Section 1931(b) because you start getting more child or spousal support, a family can get free Continuing Medi-Cal, regardless of your income, but just for 4 months. It is important that you turn in an SAR-7 or any other change reporting form explaining why you are leaving CalWORKs or Section 1931(b), to help make sure you get Transitional or Continuing Medi-Cal. The children\rquote s free Medi-Cal continues until their next scheduled annual redetermination.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 7. Former Foster Children}{\fs20 \par If you were in Foster Care on or after your 18th birthday and you were "emancipated," you are automatically eligible for free Medi-Cal until you turn 21 even if your income goes up. Chldren leaving foster care before their 18th birthday are not eligible for this program. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 8. If You Get A Notice That Medi-Cal Will Be Cut Off}{\fs20 \par DHA must send you a written notice of action at least 10 days before it cuts off, denies, delays or reduces your Medi-Cal benefits. The notice explains the reason for their action and your right to ask for a fair hearing. (See pg. 67 Hearings and Complaints).\par When a change occurs affecting your Medi-Cal eligibility, DHA must determine whether you are eligible for any other type of Medi-Cal, before sending you a notice of action cutting off your benefits. They have to look in your available records, including CalWORKs, CalFresh and other records for any missing necessary information. DHA can send you a form that only asks for the information it needs; it cannot ask for information it already has or does not need to determine whether you are still eligible for Medi-Cal. \par DHA must give you at least 30 days to complete the form. If you do not send in a completed form, DHA will send you a written notice of action that you will lose your Medi-Cal benefits. If your form is incomplete, DHA must first try to contact you by telephone and writing to get missing information before it cuts your benefits. If you send in your form within 30 days of being cut from Medi-Cal, and that information shows you were still eligible, DHA must restore Medi-Cal benefits without making you reapply.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 9. If You Move}{\fs20 \par You must report a move to the Medi-Cal worker right away. You should have no break in service if you move within California. If you move to a new county, report to DHA and also to the welfare office in the new county, and the counties will manage the transferring of your case. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 10. If You Were Billed Twice}{\fs20 \par The doctor or health service provider cannot bill both you and Medi-Cal for the same care. If you think your doctor has billed you unfairly, you should contact Legal Services. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 11. Lost or Stolen Cards }{\fs20 \par Notify your Medi-worker and a replacement card will be sent to you. If there is a medical emergency, you may receive a written notice of eligibility at your welfare office. \par \par \par \par \par There are two ways to receive your medical care under Medi-Cal in Sacramento County:\par \rdblquote Fee for service\rdblquote  (regular Medi-Cal), or Geographic Managed Care (GMC) which gives services through private health plans.   Medi-Cal participants except for people on SSI and people in long term care must use GMC.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1.\u8239 ? Fee for Service (Regular Medi-Cal)}{\fs20 \par In Fee for Service Medi-Cal you can use any doctor, clinic, hospital, pharmacy or other provider willing to accept Medi-Cal. You must tell the doctor or clinic that you have Medi-Cal before you get care. If you don\rquote t, the provider can legally bill you for all services that you get. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Geographic Managed Care}{\fs20 \par In Sacramento County, everyone except people in nursing homes or people who ask for and are given special permission must use \ldblquote geographic managed care\rdblquote  (GMC) for their physical health issues.\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 When you join a GMC plan, you must see the doctors, pharmacists and hospitals that are part of your plan. You must select a GMC plan.  Unless you have an emergency, you must get approval for all care from your GMC  provider.  The GMC will receive money each month for your health care even if you don\rquote t get services. The GMC is responsible for providing or making arrangements for you to get all Medi-Cal covered services. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3.Dental Care}{\fs20 \par Due to severe budget cuts by the state, only children, pregnant women, and persons in long term care can get Medi-Cal coverage for dental services. See page 31 for Dental Clinics.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. How to Choose a GMC Plan}{\fs20 \par When you first enroll in Medi-Cal you will get a packet in the mail. The packet will contain a form for you to choose a GMC Plan.  You will be able to choose one of five GMC Plans: Kaiser, HealthNet, Molina and  Blue Cross.\par  Fill it out the \ldblquote choice form\rdblquote  and return it.  It\rquote s a good idea to send the form by certified mail. If you don\rquote t complete the form and return it within 30 days, the state will choose a GMC Plan for you.  \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 5. Hearings, Grievances, and Leaving a GMC Plan }{\fs20 \par If your HMO denies services or you are not satisfied with the services, you have many options. You can file a grievance with your GMC Plan.  Your HMO must tell you how to file a grievance. The GMC Plan must resolve your grievance within 30 days, or less if you have an emergency. If you are still not satisfied complain in writing to the Department of Managed Health Care HMO Help Center, IMR Unit, 980 Ninth Street, Suite 500, Sacramento, CA 95814-2725. Their phone number is   (888) HMO-2219, TDD (877) 688-9891. You can also go to their website at  www.hmohelp.ca.gov.\par You have the right to ask for a fair hearing to dispute anything the GMC Plan does. (see page 67, "Hearings and Complaints.") While waiting for a state hearing, the GMC Plan must continue to provide medical services to you.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 6. Mental Health Managed Care}{\fs20 \par Mental Health services for Medi-Cal recipients are also provided through a managed care system operated through \ldblquote Local Mental Health Plans\rdblquote  in each county.  For further discussion of these services (see page 32 \ldblquote Mental Health Services.\rdblquote )\par \par \par \par If you are between 12 and 21 years old and a citizen or legal resident, you can apply for \ldblquote Minor Consent  Services\rdblquote  to get free and confidential medical treatment without parental consent related to:\par \'95\u8239 ?
Drug or alcohol abuse treatment or counseling (except methadone treatment) \par \'95 Sexually transmitted diseases \par \'95 Pregnancy and abortion \par \'95 Family planning \par \'95 Outpatient mental health (not overnight in a hospital) \par \'95 Sexual abuse\par Your parents won\rquote t be required to give information about their income or resources or pay toward the medical services, unless you want Medi-Cal for services other than those listed above. \par DHA won\rquote t tell your parents or send Medi-Cal mailings to your home without your permission. These services can be used by minors even if they already have Medi-Cal or any other health program.  \par To apply, fill out the regular Medi-Cal application and another short form for Minor Consent Services at DHA or with a DHA Eligibility Worker at the site where you are receiving care. You will have to fill out a new short form each month you need treatment, except for mental health services. For that, you need a letter from a mental health professional explaining that you meet certain conditions for getting mental health services and how long you will need treatment. You will still have to complete the short form each month to update your eligibility.\par If you already get Medi-Cal through your parents\rquote  case, you may already have a plastic Medi-Cal card. But don\rquote t use the plastic card for Minor Consent services. You will be sent a temporary card to use instead.\par \par }
