{\f8\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b0\i0\cf2\outl0 \par Medicare is a federal health insurance program. There are three parts to the program: \ldblquote Part A\rdblquote  (hospital insurance), \ldblquote Part B\rdblquote  (medical insurance), and \ldblquote Part D \ldblquote  (prescription drug insurance). The general information number is \par (800) 633 4227. The premiums in this section are for accurate for 2013. }
{\f8\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i0\cf2\outl0 \par \par 1. Part A : Hospital Insurance\par \par }\pard\plain \s7\f9\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx225\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs20\b0\i0 You are automatically eligible for Medicare Part A free of charge if you are one of the following:\par \'95     You are 65 or older and are eligible for Social Security retiree benefits based on your own or your spouse\rquote s employment \par \'95     You are a federal employee who retired after 1982 and have enough quarters of coverage \par \'95    You have been receiving Social Security Disability Income payments for 24 consecutive months\par \'95     You are age 50 or older and are a disabled widow or widower who has received Social Security through your spouse for at least 2 years \par \'95     You have end-stage kidney disease, or you have Lou Gehrig's disease (in either case, you still must have worked enough quarters, however, even though you don\rquote t need to be 65) \par \par People who are not automatically eligible for Medicare Part A may enroll voluntarily if you meet all of the following three requirements: \par \'95     You are 65 or older and \par \'95     You are a U.S. citizen, or a legal alien who has resided in the U.S. continuously for at least five years and\par \'95     You purchase both Parts A and B of Medicare, or you purchase Part B only. You may not purchase Part A only. \par }
