\par 1. Filing For Unemployment\par }{\fs20 When you are unemployed, or working less than full time, and are ready, willing, and able to work, you may be eligible to receive }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 unemployment insurance (UI) benefits.}{\fs20   You can apply on line at: \par https://eapply4ui.edd.ca.gov\par (800) 300-5616 \par Before you can get paid unemployment benefits, you must: \par \'95 Have received enough wages during the base period to establish a claim.\par \'95 Be totally or partially unemployed through no fault of your own (laid off, not fired for \ldblquote misconduct\rdblquote  or having not quit without a good reason).\par \'95 Be physically able to work and actively looking for work.\par \'95 If you are attending an approved training course you are not required to look for work, be available for work or accept work while in training).\par The minimum weekly benefit amount is $40 and the maximum weekly benefit amount is $450. The normal maximum benefit period is 26 weeks.  You can request extensions of benefits up to a total of 99 weeks.\par After you apply, you must complete a Continued Claim Certification form, DE 4581 and mail it to EDD every two weeks. If you qualify you begin recieving payments.\par Attached to the check is a form for the next two weeks. If the state thinks you did not meet eligibility requirements, they will schedule a telephone interview. Then they can reduce or deny the check. If you disagree you may ask for a hearing. Also the past employer sometimes has a right to disagree with whether you are eligible and to ask for a hearing to oppose you getting a check. \par At the hearing, an impartial administrative law judge will listen to the evidence and decide whether you should get a check. About half of the people who go to a hearing win in the hearing.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Appeal Your  Denial }{\fs20 \par Just because you are fired, even for a good reason, does not mean that you should not get UI benefits. If EDD says that you are not eligible for UI benefits, you can appeal it. To show that your  actions were not misconduct, you can argue that you made a mistake,  simply could not do the job, or that the action was an isolated occurrence. Also if you can show you had a good reason to quit a job you can get benefits.  Call Legal Services for help at (916) 551-2150.\par If you appeal, keep filing your forms with EDD every week!\par Besides unemployment benefits, the EDD (State Employment Development Department) offers the following: \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 California Training Benefits (CTB) }{\fs20 allows qualified persons to receive unemployment benefits while in approved training. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Trade Adjustment Assistance Benefits}{\fs20  if workers and their industry demonstrate damage because of imports and trade agreements.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Paid Family Leave}{\fs20  for a worker to get up to six weeks of benefits for workers to take time off to be with a newborn or care for to care for a seriously ill child, spouse, parent, or registered domestic partner.\par \par \par \par \par If you have a problem at work and are a member of a union, contact your union representative. He or she can advise you about dealing with your employer or about contacting the correct government office. \par }
