{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Wage Claims: }{\fs20 You can file a wage claim with the Labor Commissioner for any amount (or in Small Claims Court for up to $7,500) if your employer does any of the following:\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?
Pays less than the current minimum wage. There are exceptions, including minors.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?Does not pay overtime. Overtime means time-and-a-half if you work more than 40 hours in a week OR more than 8 hours a day OR on the 7th day in a row. Overtime means double-time if you work more than 12 hours in a day OR more than 8 hours, the 7th day of a work in a row.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?
Takes improper deductions from your pay.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?Does not give you your last paycheck immediately upon discharge or within 72 hours if you quit and don\rquote t give 3 days notice.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?
After you lose your job, does not pay  vacation time you were promised and have earned.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?Does not pay wages owed or pays you with a check that bounces.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?
Does not give you at least 10 minutes rest break for every 4 hours work and/or a meal break of at least a half hour, which can be unpaid, if you work at least a 5 hour shift. You can get penalty money if you don\rquote t get the breaks.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 The law also gives you waiting time penalties. }{\fs20 These penalties can be up to 30 days\rquote  pay for each day after termination you have to wait to receive all wages owed to you. Wages include regular pay, overtime, vacation pay, and penalties for not getting rest or meal breaks.  \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 To reach the Labor Commissioner\rquote s office,}{\fs20  contact the State Industrial Relations Department, Labor Standards Enforcement, 2031 Howe Ave, Suite 100, Sacramento, 95825 \tab (916) 620-6330. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 The Federal Department of Labor}{\fs20  has an office that also helps people with similar problems. Its services are more limited. However, you can file an anonymous complaint with them to avoid retaliation by your employer. \par Contact the Department of Labor Sacramento office at 800 Capitol Mall, Sacramento or (916) 654-8178. This number and address is for the Department of Veterans\rquote  Employment and Training within the Department of Labor.\par It is illegal to discriminate against workers because of their race, sex, religion, national origin, citizenship, age, disability, political affiliation, or sexual orientation. It is also illegal to require sexual favors from an employee (sexual harassment). }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 If you believe you have been discriminated against, you can file a complaint at the Federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC)}
{\fs20  in person or by mail to the San Francisco office, 350 The Embarcadero Suite 500, San Francisco, 94105. You may also reach the EEOC at (800) 669-4000. Visit http://www.eeoc.gov/employees/charge.cfm for more information. \par They will investigate your complaint and may be able to help solve your problem. If your case requires court action, you will be given a letter authorizing you to file a lawsuit. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 You can also call the California Department of Fair Employment and Housing Department (DFEH)\tab \tab \tab (800) 884-1684 }
{\fs20 for discrimination and sexual harassment claims.  DFEH accepts complaints for the same reasons as the EEOC.  DFEH also accepts discrimination complaints based on sexual orientation, whether you have children, marital status and your source of income (for example whether you get welfare).\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Employers are required to provide safe, healthy work areas. }{\fs20 If you are asked to work under unsafe or unhealthy conditions, a state agency will investigate your complaint, and your employer may be fined for violating the law. Contact the California Occupational Health and Safety Administration (Cal/OSHA) office nearest your work. The offices are listed in the State Government section in the front of the phone book white pages or at  www.dir.ca.gov/dosh/DistrictOffices.htm. \par \par \par \par \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. State Disability Insurance }{\fs20 \par If you cannot work for a temporary period because of an illness or injury that is not work related, or pregnancy, you may be able to get state disability insurance benefits (SDI). These benefits can last up to one year (39 weeks for employers and self-employed people who elected SDI coverage).\par You must be unable to do your regular or customary normal work for at least eight consecutive days. You must have lost wages because of your disability or, if unemployed, have been actively looking for work. You must be under the care and treatment of a doctor during the first eight days of your disability, and to continue receiving benefits. \par You must complete and mail a \ldblquote Claim Statement of Employee\rdblquote  within 49 days of the date you became disabled. If your disability prevents you from completing the claim form, or you are filing for benefits on behalf of a disabled or dead claimant, call (800) 480-3287 for required forms and help. \par Your must also ask if your doctor needs to complete and sign the \ldblquote Doctor\rquote s Certificate\rdblquote . If your doctor will mail your completed claim to SDI, provide give him/her with an envelope addressed to the SDI office listed below. Mail your claim no earlier than 9 days,but no later than 49 days after the first day you became disabled. Mail the completed, signed \ldblquote Claim Statement of Employee\rdblquote  together with the completed, signed \ldblquote Doctor\rquote s Certificate\rdblquote  to: \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 State Disability Insurance}{\fs20 , P.O. Box 201006, Stockton, CA 95201-9006.  You can request a claim form online at\par http://www.edd.ca.gov/disability/Disability_Request_a_Claim_Form.htm or call\tab  (800) 480-3287.\par }
