{\fs20 You may not be eligible for SDI benefits if you: \par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?Are claiming or receiving asking for or getting Unemployment Insurance.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?
Are receiving workers\rquote  compensation benefits at a weekly rate equal to or greater than the amount of SDI you would get.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?
Are in jail, prison, or recovery home because you were convicted of a crime.\par \'95\u8239 ?\u8239 ?\u8239 ?Don\rquote t have an independent medical examination when asked to do so.\par \par You have the right to appeal any denial, disqualification, overpayment, or penalty. Specific instructions Information on how to appeal will be provided on the state forms you receive. If you file an appeal and you remain disabled, you must continue to complete and return continued claim certifications. \par For residents in a state-approved alcoholic recovery home or drug-free residential facility, the maximum payable period is 90 days. However, you can get SDI if your disability is related to or caused by acute or chronic alcoholism or drug abuse which you are being medically treated for. \par When your claim is received, the SDI office will notify you of your weekly benefit amount and ask for any additional information needed to determine your eligibility. If you meet all requirements, a check will be mailed to you from a central payment center. If you are eligible for further benefits, either additional payments will be sent automatically or a continued claim certification form for the next two weeks will be sent with the check. You must report income you receive, even though sometimes it does not reduce your SDI check. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Coordination with Workers\rquote  Compensation}{\fs20 \par If you also have a Workers\rquote  Compensation claim and the insurance carrier delays or refuses payments, SDI may pay you benefits while your case is pending. However, SDI will pay benefits only for the period you are disabled and will file a lien to recover benefits paid. \par SDI and Workers\rquote  Compensation are two separate programs. You cannot legally be paid full benefits from both programs for the same period. \par However, if your Workers\rquote  Compensation benefit rate is less than your SDI rate, SDI may pay you the difference between the two rates.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Long-term or Permanent Disability:}{\fs20  If you expect your disability to be long-term or permanent, lasting for more than one year, apply for SSDI and/or SSI from Social Security well before your year of SDI is over (see page 57 for Social Security Programs).\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Workers\rquote  Compensation }{\fs20 \par If you are disabled because of a work injury or as a result of unhealthy, unsafe, or stressful conditions at work, you should apply for Workers\rquote  Compensation. Workers\rquote  compensation is a no-fault system, meaning that injured employees need not prove the injury was someone else\rquote s fault. There are six basic types of workers\rquote  compensation benefits: \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 a. Medical Benefits:}{\fs20  The employer pays for the medical care resulting from the work-related injury. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 b. Temporary Disability Benefits: }{\fs20 These are paid every two weeks if you are unable to return to work within three days or are hospitalized overnight. The benefits are intended to partially replace two-thirds of the wages lost as a result of the injury, up to a maximum of $840 per week (this may be subject to change). For most injuries, payment will not last more than 104 weeks. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 c. Permanent Total Disability: }{\fs20 If you have a permanent total disability you receive disability benefits each week for life. \par d. }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0  Permanent Partial Disability: }{\fs20  The \ldblquote percentage of disability\rdblquote  is based on a medical evaluation.  You receive weekly benefits for a period that increases with the percentage of disability, from 4 weeks for a 1% permanent disability up to 694 weeks for a 99% disability. Those with a permanent partial disability of 70% or more also receive a small life pension following the final payment of permanent partial disability benefits.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 e.  Vocational rehabilitation services: }{\fs20 These services are for when you are unable to return to your former type of work after the job injury. You are entitled to these services if they can reasonably be expected to return you to suitable gainful employment. The amount you receive will be less than Temporary Disability Benefits.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 f.  Death benefits: }{\fs20 If a worker is fatally injured, the employer pays burial expenses up to $5,000 and support payments for dependents. This amount may be subject to change. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Filing a Workers\rquote  Compensation claim: }{\fs20  If you need help filing a claim or if your employer does not have this insurance, contact: \tab \par (916) 928-3101 or (800) 736-7401. \par For problems with worker comp claims:\par 160 Promenade Circle, Suite 300\tab \tab \tab \tab Sacramento, 95834\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Disability Evaluation Unit}{\fs20 \tab             (916) 928-3150\par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Information & Assistance Unit }
{\fs20 \tab  (916) 928-3158\par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Retraining and Return to Work Unit }{\fs20  (510) 286-6990\par Injured worker workshop: Held the first Tuesday of every month at 10:30 a.m.\par You may also want to hire a private attorney to help you with your claim. Many lawyers will handle this type of case even if you cannot afford to pay in advance because their fees for Workers\rquote  Compensation cases are set by law and are paid by the insurance company. If you are permanently disabled and do not expect to return to work, you may also qualify for Social Security or SSI.\par }
