{\fs20  \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Earned Income Credit (EIC)}{\fs20 \par \ldblquote The Earned Income Credit\rdblquote  (EIC) is a check that low-income working people can get from the government by filing a federal income tax return or filling out a W-5 form during the year, even if your income is so low that you do not owe federal taxes. You need a valid social security number to get this money.\par Yearly income qualifications for earned income credit can be found at http://www.irs.gov/Individuals/Preview-of-2012-EITC-Income-Limits,-Maximum-Credit--Amounts-and-Tax-Law-Updates. Note the higher income limits for married people.\par If you are receiving CalWORKs, the Welfare Office cannot count this payment as part of your income if you spend the money in the month received or the month after. For the General Assistance program, this money does count as income.\par You can also file for \ldblquote retroactive\rdblquote  payments from the past three years. If you do not owe taxes, there is no penalty for filing for the credit late (after April 15th). \par You can claim EIC on the tax form (1040 or 1040A) or you can fill out just the first side of \ldblquote Schedule EIC\rdblquote  instead and the IRS will figure it out for you. However, you may not use the 1040EZ form (the shortest form) to claim your EIC. \par For help getting the credit you can call the EIC hotline at         \tab (800) 601-5552. To get a 1040 or 1040A form for this year and past years, and to receive free tax assistance, call the IRS at  (800) 829-3676 and ask for VITA-Volunteer Income Tax Assistance. Forms are also available in libraries, post offices and other public places.\par If you choose, you can receive this payment spread out during the year in lower payroll tax deductions instead of getting it all at once at the end of the year. To do this, ask your employer to fill out a W-5 form.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0\cf2\outl0 2. Child and Dependent Care Tax Credit}{\f2\fs24\b\i0\cf2\outl0 \par }{\fs20 Families who pay for child or dependent care in order to work or look for work may be eligible for money or reduced taxes from both the federal and state governments. The dependent can be a child under the age of 13 or a dependent of any age who is unable to care for him or herself, including a disabled spouse. \par Parents will receive up to 35% of child care expenses, with certain limits. The amount you get is generally higher if your expenses are higher.\par For both the federal and state credits, you must have a social security number or an Individual Taxpayer Identification Number (ITIN). You must have income from work and must provide the social security number of the child or dependent that is receiving care, and the name, address, taxpayer identification or social security number for the person or agency providing the care. \par The state credit is limited to families that meet income requirements. These can be found at https://www.ftb.ca.gov/individuals/faq/ivr/103.shtml. There is no income limit for the federal credit.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Renter's Tax Credit}{\fs20 \par The Renter\rquote s Tax Credit is not a payment that you can receive, but a deduction that renters can make on their state income tax forms. Renters who owe no tax will get no benefit. You can access current Renter\rquote s Tax Credit requirements at https://www.ftb.ca.gov/individuals/faq/ivr/203.shtml. \par \par \par \par \par }
