{\f8\fs56\b\i0 CalWorks CalWorks\par }\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 CalWORKs provides money for children under 19 years old and the relatives caring for them. Work and training are required of most adults. Most adults can only get CalWORKs cash aid for 24 months in a lifetime (as of 1/2013), although an individual assessment will determine how many months of aid you will receive). If you qualify for cash aid, you are also entitled to Medi-Cal for healthcare and CalFresh (food stamps). In Sacramento County, the CalWORKs agency is called DHA, the Department of Human Assistance.\par Both one parent and two-parent families can get cash aid. In two-parent families, one of the parents must be disabled, or the parent that has earned the most money in the last two years must have worked less than 100 hours in the last four weeks before applying for cash aid. \par Children must live with a related adult and be 18 years old or under. Some 18 year olds can get cash aid until their 19th birthday if they will graduate by age 19 or have a disability that kept them from graduating.\par If you are convicted of a drug-related felony after 1997, you cannot get any CalWORKs aid for yourself, but your children can still get cash aid.\par For more information about CalWORKs, see the CalWORKs Fact Sheet on the DHA website: www.dha.saccounty.net.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Limits on Property and Resources}{\fs20 \par There are property limits (\ldblquote resource limits\rdblquote ) for families, including specific limits for family members 60 years or older who are on aid. Visit http://www.dha.saccounty.net/benefits/Documents/CalWORKsFactSheet.pdf to access the current property limits.\par \'95 There is a limit on the value of a car you own if you apply for CalWORKs.  There are certain exceptions for cars, such as a car you live in, a car you need for a business, or a car used to transport a disabled person.\par The maximum grant is cut dollar for dollar by any \ldblquote unearned\rdblquote  income you have, such as social security survivor\rquote s benefits, interest (like on a bank account), or unemployment money. Earned income, wages from work, or income based on a disability is not counted dollar for dollar, although the first $225 of disiblity or earned income will not count. Half of the remaining earned income after this amount will not count. (www.lsnc.net/fact_sheets/2013_CW_changes.pdf)\par Families that have a disabled parent qualify for the higher \ldblquote exempt\rdblquote  amount. See the CalWORKs Fact Sheet on the DHA website for more information: www.dha.saccounty.net.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Think About Time Limits Before You Take Cash Aid}{\fs20 \par You may not want to get cash aid if you have other income. Any month you get cash aid counts against the 24-month time limit, even if you are entitled only to a few dollars a month. You can get Medi-Cal, Food Stamps and child care money even when you do not get cash aid. Is the cash aid you will get worth \ldblquote using up\rdblquote  a month of eligibility? Should you \ldblquote save\rdblquote  the month in case you need it more at a later time in your life? Call Legal Services to discuss your options.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. Maximum Family Grants (\ldblquote MFG\rdblquote )}{\fs20 \par You will not get more cash aid for children born while your family is getting CalWORKs. There are certain exceptions. Ask the worker or consult with a legal aid organization.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \par \par \par 1. Income Limits}{\fs20 \par You can qualify for assistance if you meet certain income requirements. Once you begin to get assistance you can get more income, but there is still a limit. There is a special calculation if you have your own business or are self-employed. You should apply even if you are not sure that you qualify. For more information, please see the CalWORKs Fact Sheet on the DHA website: www.dha.saccounty.net.\par  \par }
