{\f8\fs28\b\i0                  \par }\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \par 1. Basic Benefits}{\fs20 \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95Medi-Cal }{\fs20 to pay for health care (pg. 22: Medi-Cal)\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 CalFresh (Food Stamps) }{\fs20 in most cases (pg. 11: CalFresh) \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Immediate Needs: }
{\fs20 an advance of up to $200 at the time you apply, or your whole check within 3 days if you have an eviction notice (Tell your worker when you first apply.)\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Homeless and Housing Assistance}{\fs20  including eviction prevention, temporary shelter, move-in costs, rent subsidy, and help with cost of moving. With some exceptions, you can only get this once in your lifetime.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Non-Recurring Special Needs: }{\fs20 You can get up to $600 each time if you have to replace clothing or household items because of a fire, disaster, theft or other event beyond your control. You can also get this money for shelter if your home is so damaged or unlivable you can\rquote t stay there. You must have less than $100 to get this money.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Special Needs: }{\fs20 You can get an extra $9 to $15 if you have special needs such as higher food costs because of a necessary special diet, or higher transportation or utility costs due to a medical condition.  Breast-feeding mothers can add $15 to their grant to help with their dietary needs. Tell your worker if you have these special needs.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Welfare To Work }{\fs20 Services such as counseling, job training, help finding work educational assistance, money for tools, uniforms, childcare, transportation, and housing relocation. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Money For Pregnant Women:}{\fs20  After 6 months of pregnancy if you have no other children on CalWORKs, you may get an additional $47 until the baby is born. (Special rules apply)\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Child Support:}{\fs20  You can get $50 extra each month if the other parent pays at least $50 of child support to the County\rquote s Department of Child Support Services on time. The Department of Child Support Services should give you a list that shows when the other parent paid (an \ldblquote accounting\rdblquote ).  \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Diversion Payments}{\fs20 \par Instead of going on to cash aid you can apply for a large amount of money called a \ldblquote diversion payment\rdblquote  to help you get or keep a job. Ask your worker for details. If they tell you Sacramento County does not offer diversion, call Legal Aid (see pg. 70). \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Immediate Need}{\fs20 \par You can get cash aid of $200 or your whole check in an emergency. You must have less than $100 and \ldblquote immediate needs\rdblquote  when you apply or before you are approved. Be sure to tell the worker all of your needs, including money for diapers, medicine, transportation, laundry, or a utility shutoff notice.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. Foster Care (Someone Else's Children)}{\fs20 \par If you are caring for someone else\rquote s children, the children may qualify for Foster Care payments even if you are related to them. If a relative\rquote s children live with you but do not get foster care, you should be able to get cash aid for them.\par }
\pard\plain \s6\f12\fs56\ltrpar\qc\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx225\facenter\sl668\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf2\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs28\b\i0\outl What Are The Benefits?\par How Do I Apply for CalWorks?\par }\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 You can apply for CalWORKs at the nearest DHA office (see page 68 - DHA Offices) or online at https://www.mybenefitscalwin.org. \par When you apply, you have a right to be treated with courtesy and without discrimination for any reason. The DHA workers must try to get you all the benefits for which you are eligible.  \par Often, eligible people who urgently need the aid don\rquote t get correct information, or don\rquote t understand or get discouraged. If that is happening to you, be strong, insist on talking to a supervisor or the supervisor\rquote s manager, seek out the help of someone who will advocate for you, or call a Legal Aid office. (See page 67 - Hearings and Complaints.)\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Domestic Violence}{\fs20 \par If you are a victim of domestic violence, or suffering effects of past domestic violence tell the worker right away, because there are specially trained workers available to help you. Also, you may not need to do WTW or have other eligibility rules changed such as the Maximum Family Grant rule. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Special Help for the Disabled }{\fs20 \par If you have a physical or mental disability that makes it hard for you to go through the regular application process, DHA must give you special help. This might include: taking an application at your home, helping you fill out forms, reading all forms to you. Ask your worker for this help. If they won\rquote t give it to you, contact the Civil Rights Liaison in the office or call Legal Services for help.  \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Documents To Bring When You Apply}{\fs20 \par When applying for CalWORKs, bring the following documents with you. If you do not have some of them, go ahead and apply, and get a list of documents to be brought in later. Ask the worker to help you obtain missing documents. \par \'95 Identification with your name and current address on it. This can be a birth certificate, driver\rquote s license, California ID card\par  \'95 Social Security Numbers or Cards (or proof of application for the cards) \par  \'95 Proof of income (like check stubs, a W2, or copy of your tax return)\par  \'95 Proof that you live in the county (a document that has your name and an address on it) for each person on the application \par  \'95 If you do not have ID, you can also fill out a form to swear that you are who you say you are. DHA will use this temporarily until you get proof of identification\par  \'95 Proof of citizenship, alien or immigration status for each person on the application that has it \par  \'95 Proof of your housing situation (rent receipts, lease agreement, etc.)\par  \'95 Auto payment papers and registration\par  \'95 Letters from a doctor if anyone in the household is pregnant, disabled, has a special medical need or needs a special diet\par  \'95 Any papers having to do with marriage, divorce, child support, or other circumstances that apply to your family.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. Fingerprint Requirement}{\fs20 \par All adults (age 18 and over) and teen parents must be fingerprinted in order to apply for and get CalWORKs. If you refuse to be fingerprinted, your cash aid will be denied, or stopped if you're already getting it. If you are scheduled for fingerprinting on a day that will not work for you, ask to reschedule.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 5. Next Steps}{\fs20 \par Keep in touch with your DHA eligibility worker and write down his or her name, phone number, and phone hours. If you are asked to mail additional papers to the welfare office, ask the worker for a stamped envelope addressed to him or her. \par If you take in papers, get a receipt. Keep your own copy of all the paperwork. If you need help and your worker is not available, the Worker of the Day should help you. \par Within 45 days of when you turn in your application, you must either receive your first payment, or a notice that you have been denied aid. If the DHA denies your aid, they must send you a letter explaining the reason. Do not sign a \ldblquote withdrawal\rdblquote  of your application unless you understand and agree with the written reason you are given.\par If you are approved for cash aid for yourself, you will be required to participate in WTW unless you qualify to be excused (also called "exemption" or "good cause"). You will be getting an appointment letter to WTW shortly after you are approved for cash aid.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 6. EBT Card}{\fs20 \par DHA will give you an EBT \ldblquote electronic benefits card\rdblquote  (Golden State ADVANTAGE) to use at banks, ATM machines and stores. You access your cash aid and food stamps ("CalFresh") through the EBT card. Ask your worker for a list of banks and ATMs near you that will not charge you a fee. Call (877) 328-9677 right away if the card is stolen, lost, or destroyed.  You can get back aid used after reporting the loss.\par \par \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 \par \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Report on a \ldblquote SAR-7\rdblquote }{\fs20 \par The Quarterly Report (QR-7) has been replaced with a Semi-Annual Report (SAR-7). Every six  months, you must  report changes in income, property or the number of people in your household. DHA will mail you a SAR-7 report form for you to do this.  The SAR-7 will also ask you to report any changes, including changes you expect in the next six months. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Report All Your Income And Gifts}{\fs20 \par You should be careful to report all income you get or changes in your family. The welfare department will check bank, employer, and tax records to check your income, and accepts tips of suspected \ldblquote welfare fraud\rdblquote  from the public.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Cooperate with Child Support Collection}{\fs20 \par Unless it could put you or your children in danger to do so, parents on cash aid must help (\ldblquote cooperate with\rdblquote ) the Department of Child Support Services (DCSS) to collect child support from any absent parent. You must provide information you have about the other parent. You will get your CalWORKs grant plus an extra $50 per month for every month the other parent pays on time. \par If you do not cooperate and do not have a good reason (such as fear of the other parent), your grant will be reduced 25%.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. Get Immunizations (\ldblquote Shots\rdblquote ) For Your Children}{\fs20 \par When you apply for CalWORKs or at your annual redetermination, you must show proof that your children under age 6 have had their shots. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 5. Keep School-Age Children in School}{\fs20 \par If your child is under 16 and not attending school regularly without good cause, the adult\rquote s cash aid will be cut off. If your child is over 16 and not attending school, or welfare to work activities, without good cause, only that child\rquote s aid will be cut. In either case, the cash grant will be restored when you prove to DHA that the child is in school or has good cause. \par \par \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Weekly Participation Hours}{\fs20 \par The following rules apply to most families. As of January 2013, if you are a single parent with a child under 6, you have to work or participate in \ldblquote welfare to work\rdblquote  activities 20 hours a week, unless you are excused.\par If you are a single parent with no children under 6, the participation requirement is 30 hours a week unless someone is exempt. Two-parent families must work 35 hours, which may be shared by both parents, but one parent must do at least 20 hours or more per week.\par If your child is under two years old, one adult per family may be excused from welfare to work activities (this can only occur once in the adult\rquote s lifetime. \par If you are exempted for caring for a child between 12 and 23 months old or two children under 6 before January 2013, this exemption continued until you are called in to be \ldblquote reengaged\rdblquote  in Welfare-to-Work as a mandatory participants (when reengaged, your 24 months of the full Welfare-to-Work activities will start; see below).\par If you have used the one-time child under 2 exemption, you can still be exempt for caring for a child 3-12 months old. The length of time you are exempt will depend on your county\rquote s policy. The time will count against your limit, though. (see www.lsnc.net/fact_sheets/2013_CW_changes.pdf)\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 If you need Mental Health, Substance Abuse or Domestic Violence Services, they can count towards your hours (or you can be excused or do fewer hours). \par DHA must give you an exemption from WTW, meaning you do not need to do WTW, if you are: \par \'95 Caring for a first child under 12 months old, or any later child under 6 months old\par \'95 Pregnant, and DHA agrees with medical verification that the participation or work will harm your pregnancy\par \'95 Under 16 years old\par \'95 A full time volunteer in the Volunteers in Services to America (VISTA) program.\par \'95 You are a youth who is not pregnant or parenting and is 16 to 18 years old\par \'95 You are disabled for 30 days or more \'96 can mean physically or mentally unable to particiapte for 20/30 hours per week for participation or work as verified by a doctor\par \'95 You are 60 years or age or older\par Any months exempted for the following reasons do not count against your CalWORKs 48 month time clock;\par If you do not qualify for an exemption, you may have good cause that excuses you from doing something WTW asks you to do. The 48-month time limit is not stopped by good cause (except see below on domestic violence). \par Good cause includes:\par \'95 Not getting supportive services you need (such as child care and transportation) to work or go to a WTW activity\par \'95 Child sick at home from school\par \'95 No transportation (for example your car broke down)\par \'95 You are homeless \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Domestic Violence Waiver:}{\fs20 \par DHA can waive some of the CalWORKs rules for victims of domestic violence, such as stop the 48 month time clock, not participate in WTW, stop child support collections, or waive the maximum family grant rule. The violence can be something that happened in the past or in the present.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Learning Disabilities}{\fs20 \par All WTW participants must be offered a learning disability (LD) screening. \par You can say you do not want the LD screening, but if you change your mind, you can ask for LD screening and evaluation anytime.  \par If the evaluation shows you have a learning disability, your welfare-to-work plan must have activities that help you deal with your learning disability, such as tutoring or extra study time. DHA must decide whether job search will be useful for you, or if your time limits should be extended.\par \par \par At present the services include:\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Child care }{\f8\fs20\b0\i0 (see pg. 51)}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Transportation Money:}{\fs20  bus fare, parking costs, mileage payment, or funds to fix a car (if funding is available) \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Money for tools, books, fees, and uniforms}{\fs20  if needed for work or training. DHA does not pay for tuition.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Mental Health Services:}{\fs20  You should receive a mental health screening during orientation. Also, a DHA worker can suggest to you that you go to a mental health evaluation if they think you have a mental health barrier to finding or keeping a job. You can also ask for mental health evaluation anytime by calling your eligibility worker or WTW worker. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Substance Abuse Services: }{\fs20 You can ask for help with substance abuse treatment at anytime by calling your eligibility worker or WTW worker. If you find it hard to get or keep a job because of problems with alcohol or drugs, the DHA worker can refer you to a substance abuse clinical assessment. You may get help through a variety of rehabilitation services. You can continue getting these services as part of your WTW requirements while receiving cash aid.\par You can go to a substance abuse treatment program as the WTW activity. You have the right to refuse any substance abuse treatment program as the WTW activity; however, if you do not go to a treatment program, you cannot use substance abuse as a reason to not work or not participate in WTW.\par \par \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Orientation and Appraisal}{\fs20 \par Soon after you apply for cash aid, you will get an appointment letter to go to WTW orientation.  During the orientation, you will be told about WTW rules, time limits, and work requirements.\par After Orientation, you will meet with your WTW worker in a one-on-one meeting called Appraisal. You will talk to your worker about your work and educational history, what kind of services you need (such as substance abuse, mental health, or if you are a victim of domestic violence), and anything else that will help you get the services you need in welfare-to-work. \par If you are already enrolled in an education or training that may qualify as a Self-Initiated Program, you need to tell your worker at Appraisal. This will let you do the education and training as your WTW activity instead of going through Job Club (see next column) and the rest of the WTW process.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Job Club}{\fs20 \par Unless you are already in school or working, Job Club will probably be your first WTW activity. Job Club is a four week activity. The WTW worker can shorten the job search requirement if they think it will not help you find a job.\par You don\rquote t have to do job search if:\par \'95 It would interfere with a full time job you already have\par \'95 You are enrolled in a Self-Initiated Program of college or vocational training\par \'95 You are in the Cal-LEARN program\par \'95 Doing a job search would not help you (example: you need basic English or literacy training first)\par \'95 You need other help with domestic violence, mental health, or substance abuse.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Assessment and WTW plan}{\fs20 \par If you don\rquote t find a job in the first three weeks of job club, at the end of that week, you will have a \ldblquote vocational assessment\rdblquote  to determine your next WTW activities. \par The worker will then come up with a WTW Plan based on your individual goals and needs. Don\rquote t sign the WTW plan unless you understand and agree with it. Get a copy of it. The plan must be based on the assessment of your needs and skills. Ask for a hearing, a third party assessment, or call Legal Aid, if the plan is not what you want. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. Self Initated Programs}{\fs20 \par If on the date of your WTW appraisal you are already in school or training, or have enrolled to start school, your education or training can count as your WTW activity. This is called a SIP (\ldblquote Self Initiated Program\rdblquote ) because you chose it yourself. It could be a college or vocational program. If you already have a 4-year college  degree, you cannot do a SIP unless it is for a teaching credential.\par If you are a SIP, you will not have to follow the core/non-core activities requirement.  \par DHA has a list of approved SIP programs.  If you are in a program that is on the approved list, DHA must approve it. If the program you are in is not on the approved list, DHA should approve it if it leads to employment. You need either a letter from a college counselor or letters from three people in your field of study stating that your program will lead to employment for DHA to approve it.\par To continue in a SIP you must be making satisfactory progress toward a degree or certificate that leads to employment.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 5. Help To Keep The Job\'97Post Employment Services }{\fs20 \par Once you have found a job, the WTW program can help you with money for transportation, training,  tools, uniforms, and similar costs. WTW may be able to provide you limited help after you stop getting CAlWORKs because you found a job. You may be able to get two years of child care payments. You must ask for this money to get it. \par You may also continue to get Medi-Cal and CalFresh benefits after you leave CalWORKs, even if your income is too high.\par }
\pard\plain \s6\f12\fs56\ltrpar\qc\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx225\facenter\sl668\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf2\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs28\b\i0\outl What Are The Requirements?\par What Are The Work Rules?\par Services for Working Parents\par Welfare-to-Work Program\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 \par \par In January 2013, a new Welfare-to-Work (WTW) 24-Month Time Clock was established within the CalWORKs 48-Month Time Limit. Your own time limit will be based on an assessment. The aid does not have to be used 24 months in a row. After the adult has been aided 24 months, their part of the grant is cut, but their children can still get aid. \par People already on CalWORKs before 1/1/2013 will have up to 24 months, or whatever time is left on their 48 month clock, to finish their educational activities in their welfare-to-work plan. If you finish your educational activities and have time left on your 48 months limit, you must do federal activities (generally work) in order to keep getting aid. (see www.lsnc.net/fact_sheets/2013_CW_changes.pdf) \par Certain months do not count against the 24 months of activities. They may count against the 48-month limit, though. These are 1.) if you are developing your work plan; 2.) have good cause for not participating; 3.) are on sanction; or 4.) you are meeting the federal rules for work participation (for single adult families, this means doing 20 hours of work or the first 12 months of vocational education). (see www.lsnc.net/fact_sheets/2013_CW_changes.pdf)\par The 24-month limit can be extended if all adult parents or caretaker relatives in the home of the aided child meet any of these tests:\par \'95 60 years or older\par \'95 Disabled, receiving State Disability  Insurance, Temporary Workers\rquote  Compensation, In-Home Supportive Services or SSI, and unable to work or go to WTW\par \'95 Not able to go to WTW or employment because of an \ldblquote impairment\rdblquote , for example a learning disability or chronic mental illness. You must have a history of \ldblquote full cooperation\rdblquote  in WTW for a sustained period.  Full cooperation means no sanctions and satisfactory attendance. \par However, even with a sanction this exemption can be granted if you were ever in WTW for 6 months straight, or if you were in WTW for two periods within a two year period that are equal to six or more months.\par \'95 There are no local jobs that accommodate your disabilities\par \'95 A non-parent relative taking care of a child \ldblquote at risk of foster care placement\rdblquote  and that limits your ability to go to WTW or employment. Example, if you are a grandparent under age 60 who cannot both be regularly employed and care for the child, DHA can continue your CalWORKs aid rather than having the child enter foster care.\par \'95 A domestic abuse survivor who cannot do WTW because of the abuse. You do not have to be in a domestic abuse situation now. You will also qualify if you are suffering from the effects of past abuse and the effects limit your ability to go to WTW or work.\par You only need to tell your worker (\ldblquote self-declare\rdblquote ) about the domestic abuse; no other proof, not even a police report, is required unless the County has proof the information you gave was questionable. Your time will be extended for as long as you continue to suffer from the effects of the abuse or are in danger of more violence.\par \'95 Taking care of an ill or disabled household member if DHA agrees that this harms your ability to participate or work. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Clock Stoppers or Exemptions}{\fs20 \par Apply for an exemption to \ldblquote stop the clock\rdblquote  for any months which should not have been counted in your time limit. Your request should be in writing, but can be verbal.   \par DHA has to send you a written decision within 15 days of the request (unless something happens that is beyond the DHA\rquote s control). If you disagree with the decision you may request a state fair hearing.  DHA is required to look at your case records before asking you to provide information or documentation which you already turned in. \par Months that do not count toward your time limit include:\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Sanctioned or No Check}{\fs20 \'97Any month you do not get a CalWORKs aid payment for yourself even if you receive various services like child-care or job training or counseling. No payment is issued for you if you are sanctioned that month, the payment would have been less than $10, or you are caring for an aided child but not aided yourself. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Disabled}{\fs20 \'97Any month you are sick, disabled, or injured for over 30 days and it interferes with going to work or WTW. You may be required to provide a doctor\rquote s report. This includes mental and physical illness. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Caring For a Sick Family Member}{\fs20 \'97Any month you are caring for an ill or disabled person living in the home and that caretaking interfered with regular employment or participation in WTW activities.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Foster Child Placement or Risk of Placement}{\fs20 \'97Any month you are a non-parent relative taking care of a child who is a dependent ward of the court or \ldblquote at risk of foster care placement\rdblquote  and that responsibility interfered with regular employment or participation in WTW activities. This can exempt, for example, a grandparent under age 60 who could not both be regularly employed and care for the child.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Domestic Violence}{\fs20 \'97Any month you cannot participate in CalWORKs as a result of domestic abuse. You do not have to be in a domestic abuse situation now. You also qualify if you are suffering from the effects of past abuse. You only need to tell your worker [\ldblquote self-declare\rdblquote ] to qualify; no other proof, not even a police report, is required.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Over 60}{\fs20 \'97 Any month the  parent or caretaker relative is 60 years or older.\par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Child Support Repaid}
{\fs20 \'97All child support paid to the County by an absent parent takes time off your clock.  Ask the Department of Child Support Services to give you with an accounting of the amount of child support they have collected on your behalf during the 48-month period. Then ask your WTW worker or fill out and submit an exemption form to find out how many months of credit you get for the child support that was paid.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Teen Parent}{\fs20 \'97Any month you are a teen parent or pregnant, under age 19, do not yet have a GED or high school diploma, and either participate in or are excused from Cal Learn or another teen parent program approved by the DHA. You can be excused from Cal Learn in any month in which you can show the DHA you do not have necessary childcare or transportation, you are sick, disabled, or expelled and an alternative school program is not available. You can\rquote t use Cal Learn as a clock-stopper after you get the GED or diploma. When there is no funding the Cal Learn program is not offered.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \'95 Native American}{\fs20 \'97You are a Native American who lives in \ldblquote Indian Country\rdblquote , or on a reservation if 50% or more of the adults there are unemployed.\par In a family with two aided parents, both adults must meet one of the above clock stoppers for the month not to count. \par \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 \par If you don\rquote t follow the rules, you may have your assistance stopped. Your children\rquote s assistance should continue.\par In some cases both parents can have their cash aid cut. \par DHA can cut your part of the grant if they can show that you have:\par \'95 Failed or refused to participate in your assigned activity\par \'95 Failed to make good progress in your assigned activity\par \'95 Failed or refused to accept a job\par \'95 Failed or refused to keep a job\par \'95 Failed to keep the same amount of earnings\par DHA must try to contact you and give you a chance to comply. If you fail to comply, DHA will send you a \ldblquote Notice of Action\rdblquote  no sooner than 30 days before the cut in aid will take place. They will give you an appointment within 20 days to discuss the problem with your worker. \par It is very important for you to go to this meeting or call your worker to explain. You also have the right to ask for a fair hearing if you can\rquote t work it out with your worker.\par Your part of the grant will be cut until DHA agrees that you are complying with the rules.\par Your cash aid cannot be cut if you have good cause for refusing to comply.\par \ldblquote Good cause\rdblquote  includes:  \par \'95 You are a victim of domestic violence \par \'95 You were ill, or caring for a sick member of the family\par \'95 Your mental illness prevented you from doing what was asked of you\par \'95 You need child care for a child 12 years or younger and none is available\par \'95 Transportation is not available to your job or WTW activity\par \'95 There was discrimination at the job or training offered in terms of age, sex, race, religion, national origin, or physical \par or mental disability\par \'95 The job or job offer exceeded the daily or weekly hours of work customary for that job\par \'95 The round trip travel time to the job or activity is over two hours using public transportation, not counting time you need to take your children to school or child care\par \'95 You can only get to the activity by walking and you have to walk more than two miles round trip, not counting the distance needed to take children to school or child care\par \'95 The job or activity violates health and safety standards or does not provide worker\rquote s compensation\par \'95 Accepting the job or work activity would interrupt an approved job or training program that you have in progress\par \'95 The job or community service would result in regular employees being fired, laid off, or having their hours or pay cut.\par \'95 Any other good reason that DHA agrees will temporarily prevent or significantly impair your ability to work or participate in WTW regularly.\par During a sanction you continue to get childcare for the hours that you work. Your Medi-Cal must also continue.\par \par \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 If you are a teenager under 18 who is pregnant or who already has a child, has never been married, and you apply for CalWORKs, you must live with your own parent or parents, a guardian, another adult relative, or in an adult supervised arrangement in order to qualify.   \par If you are a teen parent, or pregnant, and don\rquote t have a high school diploma, GED or equivalent, and you receive CalWORKs cash aid, you have to be in a program called CAL-Learn. Cal-Learn provides you with supportive services in child care, transportation, and school supplies while you go to school.\par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 If your family is homeless, or has received a notice to pay or quit, the DHA can give you money for temporary shelter and to help with move-in costs to a permanent home. \par The money is in addition to your CalWORKs cash aid and does not have to be paid back.\par To apply you must be homeless or have received a notice to pay or quit: be eligible for CalWORKs and have less than $100. \par You may be asked to prove that you are homeless, but money cannot be denied or delayed if you do not have proof.\par It is against the law for any government agency to take children away from parents for being homeless unless there is evidence of abuse or neglect. Homelessness by itself is not child abuse or neglect.\par Usually you can get this homeless assistance aid only once in a lifetime. However, a family can get help more than once if the cause is:\par \'95 Domestic violence by a spouse, partner, or roommate\par \'95 A physical or mental illness (but not including drug addiction or alcoholism) and you have a written doctor\rquote s note. \par \'95 A fire or natural disaster or your home was condemned, or something beyond your control.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Temporary Shelter Money}{\fs20 \par You can get money for up to 16 days to stay in a hotel or shelter if they charge rent. You cannot use this money to pay to stay with a friend. You will get $65 to $125 per day to pay for shelter, depending on your family size. If you find some place for less money than they give you, you can keep the extra money. \par Show receipts to prove that you have paid something for shelter. (If you cannot show receipts, you can still get homeless aid money but it will be paid directly to the hotel or shelter). You will also have to fill out a form showing that you have looked for a permanent place to live for each day that you received the shelter.  \par If eligible, DHA should help you the same day you apply, either by giving you a referral to a specific shelter with room for you or by giving you cash that day. If they refer you to a shelter, they must give you temporary shelter money by the next day.\par Even if you decide not to go to the shelter ask for money for as many nights as needed during a single 16-day period. (For example, you cannot get a week now and another week two months from now.) If you needed but did not get all 16 days of temporary homeless assistance, ask for a hearing to collect it retroactively. After the 16 days are over, make sure to provide your worker with a mailing address (even if only temporary) within 10 days. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Money for Permanent Housing}{\fs20 \par You can also get money to cover the actual cost of security deposits, \ldblquote last month\rquote s rent\rdblquote  deposit, and gas, electricity, and water deposits. The DHA will not pay for the first month\rquote s rent, though, or old overdue utility bills because you must pay that from your CalWORKs cash aid.  \par DHA will not pay unless you find a place where your share of the monthly rent is less than 80% of the monthly family income.\par If you plan to share your housing, the landlord must agree to the rent-share plan. DHA will question the housing unless your name is on the lease. \par If you are a CalWORKs participant now you must be given this permanent housing assistance within one working day of showing that you have found a place. If you are not yet receiving CalWORKs benefits, you must first bring in the documents you need to prove you are eligible for CalWORKs, and proof that you have found a place (like a note from the landlord or a proposed rental agreement).\par When you pay your landlord, get a receipt to give to your worker within 30 days. If you later move, the landlord and/or the utility companies should return the security deposits to you, not to the County, to use at your next residence. \par You can also get Permanent Housing Assistance to receive up to 2 months of back rent to prevent eviction. Each month of this back rent cannot be more than 80% of the family income. Call Legal Services for details (see pg 70). \par If you have questions, call 211.\par }
