{\fs20 Children between the ages of 6 and 18 are required by California law to attend school. \par The Sacramento County Office of Education and the respective school districts within Sacramento County offers numerous programs for all family members, including: \par \'95 Workforce development and employability skills training\tab \'95 Youth development programs\tab \tab \tab \tab \line \'95 Infant development programs for infants and toddlers up to 36 months of age with developmental delays\tab \tab \line \'95 Child welfare and attendance supports\tab \tab \tab }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Early Head Start }{\fs20     \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \'95 Literacy programs to help students and parents learn to read, and to train parents to help their children learn\tab \tab \'95 Computer training and job readiness for parents\tab \tab \'95 }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Early Advantage}{\fs20  programs for children under age 3\tab \tab \'95 Head Start and }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 State Preschool }
{\fs20 programs for children\line \'95 First 5 funded Preschools and Playgroups\par Call your local school district or }{\f8\fs20\b\i0
\tab (916)228-2500}{\fs20  county-wide to find out about these and other programs preschool programs and family literacy programs. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Sacramento Food Bank and Family Services \tab }{\fs20 www.sacramentofoodbank.org Parent Education Hotline (916) 313-7622. SFBFS\rquote  Parent Education program guides parents in raising children in a healthy supportive manner. After participating in workshops, families can earn baby supplies.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. After School Enrichment}{\fs20 \par Especially if you are in CalWORKs, call your local elementary school to see if it has an after-school enrichment program. This program provides supervised after-school fun, growth, snacks, and learning for children from first through sixth grade. Children must be attending the school where the program is offered.\par If your children attend school in the }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Sacramento City Unified School District}{\fs20 , call }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 (916) 643-9430}{\fs20  for information on enrollment in afterschool programs.  If your children attend school in a different school district, call the local district.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Homeless Children's Rights}{\fs20 \par Homeless children do not need a permanent address to enroll in school. They also:\par \'95 May remain at the same school they attended before becoming homeless, or enroll at the school serving the place they are living temporarily.\par \'95  Cannot be denied enrollment just because any documents are not immediately available.\par \'95 Have the right to participate in school meals,and any other federal, state or local programs for which they are eligible.\par \'95 Must be provided transportation if other children get transportation.\par \'95 Cannot be isolated or separated from the main school environment just because they are homeless.\par These special rights under federal McKinney-Vento law apply to all children and teens without a fixed, regular adequate residence including if you are staying with friends or relatives because you lost your housing, you are waiting for foster placement, or you are living in any kind of shelter, car, motel, campground, abandoned building, garage, or similar place.   \par \par \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 CalWORKs will pay for child care for children up to age 12, and up to age 21 if the child is disabled and needs special care. You may be eligible for child care even if you are under a CalWORKs sanction, and after you leave CalWORKs for up to two years. If you are low income, working, but did not ever get CalWORKs cash aid, you may still qualify for subsidized child care. For information call (916)369-0191. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. How Do I Get Child Care?}{\fs20 \par If you are receiving cash aid and participating in Welfare to Work activity with the Department of Human Assistance (DHA), ask your worker to send a Stage 1 Referral for child care, DHA will handle your child care at first. After DHA approves your case and says you are stable on aid, DHA will send your case to Child Action for Stage 2 Child Care. \par If you were on cash aid within the last 24 months and are no longer aided, you could be eligible for CAI\rquote s Stage 2 program. If you think you are eligible,}
{\f8\fs20\b\i0  call (916) 361-0511 to apply}{\fs20 . \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Choosing Quality Child Care}{\fs20 \par It is your right as a parent to choose the child care you think is best for your child. The agency will give you referrals and information on what to look for when choosing a provider. If you decide the referrals are not good choices, ask for more referrals. Choose the child care that\rquote s best for you: \par \'95 Child care centers, preschools, or family child care are licensed. \par \'95 License-exempt child care can be provided by friends, relatives, or neighbors. If you use license-exempt care, you will need to file a statement that your provider meets minimal health and safety requirements. Your provider may also need to be Trustline registered (criminal background check and fingerprinting.). The child care agency will not pay for child care provided to you by someone on your CalWORKs case.  \par \'95 If the provider is caring for children from more than one family (besides their own) they may need a license. \par Most providers will have to be Trustline registered, meaning they are fingerprinted and go through a criminal background check, before they can be paid. If the provider is the child's aunt, uncle, grandmother, or grandfather, they are exempt from the Trustline registration process. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. What is Subsidized Child Care?}{\fs20 \par Subsidized child care is assistance to low-income families to cover all or part of their child care costs.\par If you are working, enrolled in school, or participating in an approved welfare-to-work training plan, you may be eligible for financial assistance with your child care costs. There are a wide variety of programs that provide subsidized child care services for eligible families. \par Subsidized child care programs offer care for children, birth through twelve years of age. Some are full-day child care and development programs, some are part-day educational enrichment programs, and some pay for care provided by family, friends or neighbors. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b0\i0 You are eligible for subsidized child care if:}{\fs20 \par \'95 You have children under age 13 \par \'95 You are working \par }
{\fs20 \'95 You are in a training program \par \'95 You are going to school \par \'95 You have a reason why you cannot care for your own children \par \'95 Your family income meets eligibility requirements \par \'95 You want your 3-5 year-old child to attend a state preschool \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 4. How Do I Get On the Waiting List for Child Care?}{\fs20 \par Child Action, Inc. maintains a list of families who are eligible for subsidized child care programs in Sacramento County. This list is called the \ldblquote Centralized Eligibility List\rdblquote  (or CEL). By signing up on the CEL, child care programs that meet your specified needs can access your information when they have openings in their programs.\par There are two ways to apply to get on the Centralized Eligibility List (CEL):\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Online:}{\fs20  If you have access to a computer, you can submit an application through the website, \tab \tab \tab \tab http://sacramento.thecel.net.\par Follow the instructions to begin the application process. If you fill out the application on-line, you will be able to update your own information using your log-in and password.\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Phone:}{\fs20  Call (916) 369-0191 and speak with a Child Action, Inc. Information Specialist, who will assist you with determining your eligibility and filling out the CEL application. They can mail or fax a CEL application to you, or we can }
{\fs20\up8 help you fill out the online CEL application over the phone. }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \par 5. How Long Will I Have to Wait Before I Get  Help?}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20 There are thousands of eligible families that are on the Centralized Eligibility List, so there is no guarantee that you will receive financial assistance. However, the first step in receiving help paying for child care is to submit an application.\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 After you submit your application it is important to keep your information up-to-date. If your address, phone number, income, or family size changes it may affect your eligibility. You can update your information via the website    http://sacramento.thecel.net,  mail in an updated CEL application form (available on the website), or call a }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Child Action, Inc. Information Specialist}{\fs20  at}{\f8\fs20\b\i0  (916) 369-0191}{\fs20  to update your information over the phone.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 6. Speaking Up for Child Care}{\fs20 \par The most effective way to make sure that there is adequate child care assistance for families is to communicate your needs to your elected officials. Parent Voices, a parent-led group, helps parents advocate and speak out on child care issues. \par For information about Parent Voices or to receive a copy of  a publication on advocacy, call }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Child Action, Inc.}{\fs20  at \tab \tab }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 (916) 369-0191}{\fs20  and ask for Handout #9: Speaking Up For Children. You can also ask for a grievance if you disagree with what Child Action has done in your case. If you disagree with the result of the grievance you can appeal to the State Department of Education. }
