\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 \par \par \par Covered workers pay for Social Security (FICA) by being taxed on the money they earn, and employers must match this amount. Social Security covers both employees and people who are self-employed.\par The amount of Social Security you get depends on how much money you have earned and how many quarters you worked in a job covered by Social Security. As of 2014, a quarter is credited to your account for each $1,200 earned. You cannot earn more than 4 quarters in a year. Visit http://www.ssa.gov/oact/cola/QC.html for the latest coverage data.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Retirement Benefits}{\fs20 \par Monthly payments are made to workers and their eligible dependents, which include:\par \'95\u8239 ?
children under 18 \par \'95\u8239 ?children age 18 to 19 who are full time students \par \'95\u8239 ?children age 18 or over with a disability which began before age 22 \par \'95\u8239 ?
spouses and unremarried ex-spouses who are 62 or over \par \'95\u8239 ?spouses and unmarried ex-spouses caring for the worker\rquote s children who are under 16, or for children who are disabled and entitled to benefits on the worker\rquote s account. \par To get full retirement benefits you must be at least 65 years old. (This will gradually increase to age 67 by the year 2022). To receive reduced benefits, you must be at least 62. Persons over 65 receiving retirement benefits also get Medicare benefits. \par Present law prevents Social Security benefits going to any non-citizen who is not \ldblquote lawfully present\rdblquote  in the U.S. (see page 65 Guide for Non-Citizens). \par You can earn money and still get retirement benefits. If you are over 65, there is no earnings limit. If you are between 62 and 65, there are limits which can be calculated at http://www.ssa.gov/planners/. The limit increases every year. If your earnings are over the limit, your retirement benefits are \line reduced (by $1 for every $2 earned above the limit). These limits apply only to what you earn, not to money you get from investments, pensions, and other \ldblquote unearned income.\rdblquote \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Survivor Benefits}{\fs20 \par \line When a covered worker dies, monthly payments are made to eligible family: \par \'95\u8239 ?
A spouse over age 60 or disabled over age 50 or caring for the worker\rquote s child who is under 16 or disabled\par \'95\u8239 ?
The spouse above can be divorced from the worker  only if the marriage lasted at least a decade\par \'95\u8239 ?A disabled adult unmarried child \par A  parent of the worker over age 62 if at least 50% dependent on the worker.\par \par \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 \par \par If you are unable to work because of a severe illness, certified by doctors, that has lasted at least 12 months or is expected to last at least 12 months or end in death, you may be able to get Monthly Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI) payments for yourself and eligible family members (such as a spouse, unmarried ex-spouse, child, or adult disabled child). \par For these additional family members, the amount is in addition to the worker\rquote s benefit and there is a maximum amount that can be paid to any one family. \par When you become disabled you have several options. \par You may be entitled to State Disability Insurance (see pg. 40, Workers Rights and Unemployment  under "What If I Get Injured and Can\rquote t Work").\par However, you should also apply immediately for disability benefits under Social Security.  \par You may also want to apply for SSI (pg. 56 - SSI and pg. 58 - CAPI). \par SSDI does not require low family income, but SSI does. Also, SSDI provides Medicare eligibility, while SSI provides Medi-Cal. SSDI requires that the applicant have a record of at least some wages earned during each of 20 quarters (three-month periods) of covered employment in the last 10 years before becoming disabled\par SSI has no work history requirement.\par Because both SSI and SSDI can take several months from application to approval, while waiting you can also apply for \ldblquote Medi-Cal Only\rdblquote  at the welfare office. It is important not to wait until your state disability benefits have run out before applying for federal disability benefits. If you have not yet received your SSI or SSDI and your state disability benefits have run out, you should apply for General Assistance (see pg. 60).\par \par \par \par SSI (\ldblquote Supplemental Security Income\rdblquote ) is a cash benefit program for low-income persons 65 and over and for blind and disabled persons of any age, including infants and children. Some immigrants cannot qualify for SSI but can qualify for another program called CAPI (Cash Assistance Program for Immigrants.)\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Basic Eligibility }{\fs20 \par If you have enough work history you may qualify for SSDI (Social Security Disability Insurance.) If you do not have enough work history you may qualify for SSI. Many people get both: if your SSDI is below the maximum SSI amount, some SSI will be added to your check to make it come up to the SSI level.\par SSI may be your entire income, or it may add to other income you already get so long as your total income is not more than $20 over the SSI maximum benefit. You must be a U.S. citizen or a qualified immigrant living in the country legally to get SSI. \par To get SSI, at least one of the following must apply: \par \'95 You are age 65 or older \par \'95\u8239 ?
You are blind; the vision in your best eye is no better than 20/200 with glasses or your tunnel vision is 20% or less\par \'95\u8239 ?
Your medical records and/or examination by a doctor chosen by the state shows that your physical or mental disability can be expected to keep you, or have kept you, from working for 12 continuous months or can be expected to result in death \par \'95\u8239 ?
You are a child under 18 who has a medically proven \ldblquote marked and severe\rdblquote  physical or mental disability that would keep you from working if you were an adult or significantly interfere with your daily activities. \par You cannot get SSI any month in which you are in prison or jail, in violation of parole or probation, or a fugitive from a felony. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1.\u8239 ? Income  }{\fs20 \par Your \ldblquote countable income\rdblquote  may not be above the maximum benefit level. Visit www.ssa.gov/onlineservices/#a0=3 or call (800) 772-1213 to see if you qualify. \par There are many other types of income that can be subtracted, including foster care payments and all work expenses if you are blind. For a full list, see \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab http://www.ssa.gov/notices/supplemental-security-income/index.htm\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Resources or Assets}{\fs20 \par Your countable resources may not be more than a certain amount. Some resources are }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 not}{\fs20  counted, including the home you live in and one car if you use it for work or medical treatment at least four times a year or if it is specially-equipped for a disabled person. There are special rules also for property used to make income, and retirement accounts.\par If you have too many resources, you can spend them down to meet the limits. You could buy things you need (as long as whatever you buy does not make you go over another limit), or pay off  debts. If you give away  resources or sell them below a fair price, you can be ineligible for SSI for up to 36 months.\par If a child eligible for SSI lives with a parent (or parents) not eligible for SSI, a portion of the parent\rquote s income and resources may be used to figure the child\rquote s SSI cash aid. If a person eligible for SSI lives with a spouse not eligible for SSI, a portion of the spouse\rquote s income and resources may be used to figure the  SSI cash aid.  The Social Security Office can explain the complicated rules and figure the benefit. For more information, visit www.ssa.gov/onlineservices/#a0=3 or call (800) 772-1213. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Food:}{\fs20  If you get SSI in California, you cannot get CalFresh (food stamps).  However, if you live where meals cannot be prepared you can get }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 additional}{\fs20  financial help each month (ask for the Restaurant Meals Allowance.) }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \par Health Care: }
{\fs20 If you receive SSI, you automatically qualify for Medi-Cal without a share of cost. You may also be eligible for In-Home Supportive Services. (See page 32)\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Special Telephone Equipment: }{\fs20 If your disability makes it difficult to use the phone you may qualify for special equipment to help. Call (800) 806-1191 (voice) or \tab \tab (800) 806-4474 (TTY line.)\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Rent and Household Expenses: }{\fs20 Benefits will be }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 lower}{\fs20  if you live with someone else and do not pay your full share of household expenses. Homeless people receive the same cash aid as persons with homes, except that you can only get SSI 6 months out of 9 if living in a \ldblquote public shelter\rdblquote . If you were getting free room and board when you applied for SSI and later begin paying your share for room and board, tell your worker so your benefits will increase.\par A single person can get a board & care rate called \ldblquote Nonmedical Out of Home Care,\rdblquote  if you do not receive In Home Supportive Services, are not staying in your own home, and a relative who does not get SSI is providing you room, food, and personal care. The county must certify the private residence.\par You may be able to get an immediate payment from the Social Security office if either your SSI or your Social Security check is late and you need money right away. \par \par \par \par See page 58 Social Security Offices.  Come in, or call\tab \tab (800) 772-1213 to make an appointment. Even if the process from application to first check takes months, when you are approved the benefits will be paid beginning with when you started the application. Do not accept a verbal denial. Insist on filing at least a partial application. If you do not have all the necessary information, you can give additional or corrected information later. \par TTY Number for hearing impaired      (800) 325-0778. \par If you have difficulty with English or with hearing, the Social Security Office will provide you with an interpreter without cost. You may have help from  a friend, family member or advocate at any appointment.  If your condition makes getting to the office difficult, you may ask for a telephone interview. \par If you want to sign a form allowing someone else to serve as your \line representative, ask by phone for form SSA-1696 to be mailed to you. Parents or guardians can apply for a child under age 18 who is blind or who has a disability.\par You will need to provide:\par \'95\u8239 ?
Social Security card or record of number \par \'95\u8239 ?birth certificate or other proof of age\par \'95 rent or mortgage information\par \'95\u8239 ?
payroll slips, bank books, insurance policies, car registration, burial fund records \par \'95\u8239 ?names, addresses and telephone numbers of doctors\line hospitals and clinics that have treated them (if applying for SSI because of disability or blindness) \par \'95 proof of U.S. citizenship or eligible noncitizen status \par }
\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 You should apply even if they don\rquote t have all the things listed. The Social Security Office can help you get whatever is needed. \par Your case will be sent to a state agency under contract with SSA to obtain your medical records and decide whether you meet the medical requirements for eligibility to benefits. In general, people who are blind or have very obvious disabilities are approved more quickly than those who must have their disabilities more extensively verified. \par If the state  decides that you are not disabled enough to get SSI, you can appeal. \par If necessary, you can apply for General Assistance while you wait for SSI approval. Ask if  the county will help you get SSI while you are on General Assistance.\par If you get a notice that you have been overpaid, and you believe it is not your fault, insist on immediately submitting a \ldblquote Request for Waiver of Overpayment.\rdblquote \par If you believe that your SSI check or any notice that you get is wrong, insist on immediately submitting a \ldblquote Request for Reconsideration\rdblquote . Legal Services (see pg. 70) and advocacy organizations can help you best after you insist on these forms to protect your rights. There are also private attorneys who help with disability cases. \par Also, some Congressional district offices have free experts at Social Security Casework. Call yours and ask for  help with a  hearing or complaint. \par \par \par \par \par \par \par \par The Social Security Administration must mail you a notice of any changes in your benefits.  If you disagree with the proposed action, request a \ldblquote Reconsideration\rdblquote  immediately by going  to  the  Social Security office and filling out a \ldblquote Request for Reconsideration\rdblquote  form . Make sure that you get a copy of the form stamped by Social Security with the date it was filed. The form is also available online at www.ssa.gov. \par If you request a Reconsideration within the time period given on the notice (usually 10 days), your benefits can continue unchanged until you receive a decision.   If they paid you too much, and they want to take money out of your check, you can request a waiver if it wasn\rquote t your fault and if it would be hard for you to pay the money back. Ask Social Security for the waiver form. \par In SSDI cases, you must fill out a separate form asking for your aid to continue. This is called \ldblquote payment continuation.\rdblquote   If you miss the deadline given in the notice, the aid will be cut or reduced, but you still have 60 days from the date you received the notice to request a Reconsideration.  After 60 days, if you have \ldblquote Good Cause\rdblquote  for missing the deadline, you may be allowed to file a Reconsideration.  If you win the Reconsideration, your lost benefits will be paid back to you.  \par There are three types of Reconsideration: case review, informal, or formal conference.  However, if your application for SSDI or SSI is denied for medical reasons, you can usually only get a case review.  \par If your reconsideration or waiver is denied, you may request a hearing before an Administrative Law Judge (ALJ) with the Office of Disability Adjudication and Review (ODAR).  At the hearing you may  appear in person, submit new evidence, examine the evidence used in making the determination or decision under review, and present and question witnesses.  The ALJ who holds the hearing may ask you questions.  He or she will write a decision based on the hearing record.  If you waive your right to appear at the hearing, the ALJ will make a decision based on the evidence that is already in the file.\par When you are receiving SSI or SSDI and then start working, your benefits could be cut if you are working and earning too much. (This is known as \ldblquote Substantial Gainful Activity\rdblquote  or \ldblquote SGA\rdblquote ). 10 days after you get the tentative notice, a notice that your payments will stop will be sent to you. Request a reconsideration immediately. To protect yourself, it is best to make a new application at the same time you request a Reconsideration. \par If you are considering going back to work, know your rights.  Call }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Protection and Advocacy Services}{\fs20  at}{\f8\fs20\b\i0  (800) 776-5746}{\fs20  and ask for their booklet, \ldblquote Disability and Work.\rdblquote   \par \par \par \par }
