{\f8\fs28\b\i0\outl What Benefits Are Available To   Immigrants?       \par }\pard\plain \s5\f8\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb40\sa80\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Immigrants can get many kinds of help from the government even if they don\rquote t have a \ldblquote green card.\rdblquote  For help with other immigration and citizenship issues see the list of agencies at the end of the chapter on pg. 66.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 1. Benefits Available To All Immigrants\par All immigrants, }{\f8\fs20\b0\i0 including those without documents, can qualify for the following kinds of help:}
{\fs20 \par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Health Care:}{\fs20  Prenatal Care; Emergency Medi-Cal; Minor Consent Medi-Cal; Regional Centers; California Children\rquote s Service;  CHDP and Immunizations for kids.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Food Programs:}{\fs20  WIC; School Breakfast & Lunch; Help from food pantries.\par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Other Help: }{\fs20
Help from Shelters; Public Education; and services from many non-profit agencies.\par These programs don\rquote t have immigration requirements and if you are undocumented, you may qualify.  You do not need to tell anyone that you or anyone else who lives with you are undocumented.  Your workers do not need to ask about your immigration status if you are not getting benefits for yourself.  If they do ask you, simply tell them that you are a \ldblquote not qualified\rdblquote  immigrant (\ldblquote not qualified\rdblquote  is not the same as undocumented).  That is all they need to know. \par If a school or child care center asks for your social security number on a form, you can write \ldblquote none\rdblquote  on the form or leave it blank. They may not give the information on that form to a government agency.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Victims of Trafficking, Domestic Violence, and Other Serious Crimes}{\fs20 \par California law provides eligible non-citizens who are victims of trafficking, domestic violence and other serious crimes access to benefits equal to those available for refugees.\par \'95\u8239 ?
Victims of trafficking may qualify before they are certified by the federal government as victims. \par \'95\u8239 ?Victims of domestic violence and other serious crimes may qualify once they have applied for a U visa/interim relief.\par \'95\u8239 ?
You do not need a social security number to apply.\par }{\f8\fs20\b\i0 3. Benefits Available To Lawfully Present Immigrants}{\fs20
\par Most lawfully present immigrants, such as legal permanent residents, refugees, asylees, and persons granted withholding of deportation, can get CalFresh (food assistance) benefits, CalWORKS, General Assistance, County healthcare, Housing Assistance,  and Medi-Cal. If they have a sponsor, the sponsor\rquote s income may count as part of their income for five years. \par Refugees who have been in the country less than 8 months and persons who were granted asylum less than 8 months before,  can also be eligible for}
{\f8\fs20\b\i0  Refugee Cash Assistance }{\fs20 (generally this is for able bodied adults without children. Victims of trafficking may also qualify for Refugee Cash Assistance once they receive certification. Call the local DHA office listed on page 68.\par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 Social Security:}{\fs20  If you are a non-citizen who has paid into the Social Security system as a worker or had money taken out of your paycheck for this program, you may qualify for Social Security disability, retirement or survivor benefits (see Social Security, pg. 56). \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 SSI:}{\fs20  If you are a low-income non-citizen in the U.S. who has a disability is blind, or over 65 years old, you can get SSI if: \par \'95 You were lawfully residing in the U.S. on August 22, 1996, and are blind or disabled. \par \'95 You are a refugee, asylee or were granted withholding of deportation/removal, but only during the seven years after getting this status. \par \'95 You are a current or veteran U.S. military personnel \par \'95 You are a lawful permanent resident with credit for 40 quarters (about 10 years) of work in the U.S. There are special rules in which quarters worked by your spouse or parents may count; ask the worker.\par  }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 CAPI:}{\fs20  If you are an immigrant who has a disability, is blind or 65 years old or older and you are not eligible for SSI because of your immigration status, you may be able to get CAPI (Cash Assistance Program for Immigrants). See page 58. \par }
