{\f8\fs20\b\i0 \par 1. What Is Public Charge?}{\fs20 \par If you are applying to become a lawful permanent resident (green card holder) and you are using health care programs (such as Medi-Cal , In Home Supportive Services, or Healthy Families) or CalFresh, it will not hurt your chances of getting your green card by making you a "public charge".   You might have a problem getting your green card if you have used cash welfare or long-term care (like a nursing home) depending on your situation. Cash aid for your children or other family members will not effect your immigration status unless it is your family\rquote s only income. \par Officials will look at many factors, including your age, your health, your entire family\rquote s (or sponsor\rquote s) income and resources to determine whether in the future you will be likely to need to rely on cash welfare to live.  Past use of cash benefits may not count against you, for example if it was several years ago that you received the benefits or if it was only for a short period of time.\par You do not have to worry about public charge if you already have a green card (unless you leave the US for more than 6 months at a time and try to re-enter), or if you are applying for citizenship, are a refugee or asylee, or are applying for a green card based on having lived in the US since before 1972.\par Victims of domestic violence who file a self-petition under the Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) are subject to the "public charge" test. However, they can use all benefits, including cash welfare, without affecting this decision.\par The government should not demand that you repay any welfare you correctly received as a condition of giving you legal status.  If this happens, call one of the immigrant advocate agencies. \par }
{\f8\fs20\b\i0 2. Sponsors}{\fs20 \par Most new immigrants entering into the U.S. through family members are required to have a sponsor sign an \ldblquote affidavit of support\rdblquote  form.  This form is a promise to the government that the sponsor will help to provide economic support for any sponsored immigrants.  \par If you are a sponsored immigrant and you want to apply for certain government benefits, your sponsor\rquote s income and resources may be added to yours in determining your eligibility for benefits (this is called \ldblquote deeming\rdblquote ).  This deeming rule makes the income of many immigrants too high to qualify for benefits.  There is no deeming if you are applying for health care programs, only for CalFresh and cash assistance programs.  \par Deeming does not apply to some immigrants, including: refugees, asylees, parolees, victims of domestic violence who have filed a \ldblquote self-petition\rdblquote  for an immigrant visa, or certain other immigrants who are not required to have a sponsor.  In addition, some programs have exception for very low income persons called \ldblquote indigence exceptions\rdblquote . The rules for there are different for each program. Ask about this when you apply.\par If you have a question or problem with \ldblquote sponsor deeming\rdblquote  contact one of the agencies listed at the end of this page.\par \par \par If you are arrested by the Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE):\par }
